Warrensburg Athletics has received confirmation that multiple student-athletes are currently under self-quarantine for COVID-19 in more than one program.

The District has decided to suspend the strength/conditioning and sports activities at the high school and middle school. We will resume activities on July 27th. At any time, this also may be canceled. Our goal is to slow the spread and keep our student-athletes safe. Remember when we return to continue to self-monitor and let us know when an issue arises.

Thank you for your patience and understanding.

Keith Chapman

post_text:
Update 4.24.20

With the governor ordering all public schools to close for the remainder of the school year (which for our district is May 21st), and UCM cancelling all activities on campus through the end of May, this also means that we will not be holding our graduation ceremony on May 16th as scheduled.

It is our hope and intent to still have our traditional graduation ceremony. While many things are still uncertain, we have secured two dates, June 13 and July 25 as possible dates for us to celebrate graduation at UCM.

It is EXTREMELY important for everyone to realize that these dates are tentative and are for planning purposes only. The ability to gather in large groups such as graduation may be out of our control.

We are also contingency planning for other end of the year activities, such as prom, Project Graduation, etc. We will share information about these events as soon as possible.

We appreciate everyone‚Äôs continued patience as we work through the effects of the pandemic.

Thank you,

Scott Patrick
District Superintendent

post_text:
YiaSi Huang and Vicki Martins from Warrensburg High School recently attend the Missouri FCCLA Legislative Shadowing Day in Jefferson City. These two young ladies had a great day and memorable experience. They also toured the governor's mansion, state capital, and supreme court.

Missouri FCCLA members in their junior and senior years of high school who have an interest in public policy, laws and its relation to families, careers and communities are encouraged to apply for a day of job shadowing in the Missouri General Assembly. Up to 50 FCCLA members may be chosen for this program. This program is funded through Missouri FCCLA membership dues and contributions from the Missouri Educators of Family and Consumer Sciences (MoEFACS). Thanks to Senator Hoskins for his hospitality and congratulations to YiaSi and Vicki!

The students in Mrs. Ritter's first grade class at Ridge View Elementary collected items for their class Mitten Tree. Students in the Careers in Teaching class at Warrensburg High School were able to use FaceTime and observe an urban school classroom in Manteca, CA recently. They were able to research the school, demographics of the area and discuss while we observed.

In the last few weeks, they have had guest speakers from our own district, discussing their own careers in education, school law, diverse learners and much more! Dr. Patrick discussed his career and role as superintendent. Mrs. Leslie Brown, Mrs. Marty Webb and Mrs. Cassie Gates discussed their careers and current roles in education, as well as, how they help with diverse learners. These experiences were very beneficial and eye-opening to our students!

post_text:
Each year, West Central Electric sends delegates to Washington, DC for the National Rural Electric Youth Tour. To be eligible, students must attend a school in the West Central Electric service area, and write a 600-word essay on a chosen topic. Nine finalists were chosen to compete in an oral competition to determine the winners.

Warrensburg High School had three finalists chosen to compete orally: Abigail Fowler won first place, earning a trip to Washington DC as a delegate, Rylie Othic tied for third and will also attend the Washington DC Youth Tour, and as a finalist, Joshua Cymer earned an opportunity to attend CYCLE, Cooperative Youth Conference and Leadership Experience which is held for three days each July in Jefferson City. Congratulations to our accomplished students; we are proud of these achievements!

post_text: On April 9th, the Warrensburg Area Career Center hosted their fourth annual Interview Day. This event provides the opportunity for Warrensburg and sending school students to participate in Mock Interviews. WACC teams up with the Missouri National Guard (the event takes place at the Guard Armory) to teach job attainment skills, which include dress for an interview, resume writing, cover letters, references, job applications, making good choices in life and of course the interview with qualified HR community members. Thanks to everyone who participated in this event!

Sgt. Stosberg from the Missouri State Highway Patrol recently spoke to our sophomores at Warrensburg High School and discussed the main causes of crashes, how to prevent crashes and stay safe while driving. Kelly from ThinkFirst Missouri discussed an accident that left her partially paralyzed from the waist down. She discussed her life before and after her accident and how she could have made better choices to prevent this from happening.

Thank you to the MSHP and ThinkFirst Missouri for this presentation.

post_text:
Below are photos from Mrs. Sentgeorge's 1st semester Pet Portraits project at Warrensburg Middle School. This year, a majority of students chose to display their work in Western Missouri Medical Center because they wanted to explore the healing role of art and the role our pets have in our health. Some of the pets weren't complete in the photo but they are now finished!

Each student was responsible for painting their own canvas, made changes based on peer-critique, and then presented a reflection statement to the class. If you see any of these students, please congratulate them on their efforts! Works are on display at WMMC and WMS (5 paintings) until the end of March. At that time, paintings will be returned to students to take home.

A special thanks goes to the Warrensburg Schools' Foundation for funding from the Classroom Impact Grant and to Western Missouri Medical Center for allowing students to display their work! Great job everyone!

post_text:
In conjunction with Anti-Bullying month and Red Ribbon Week, Warrensburg Middle School hosted guest speaker, Jackie Moore. In June, Jackie and her husband began Jordyn‚Äôs #summershirtproject to help their daughter--a 17 year old with autism-- learn basic job and life skills by asking friends to purchase a ‚ÄúBe Kind to Everyone‚Äù shirt. Jordyn rolls the shirts, adds a wristband, puts them in the package and signs a thank you card to add to each package.

Jackie encouraged the students of WMS to #bekindtoeveryone and shared that sometimes the greatest gift you can give to someone is to include them. Her message also included making good choices on social media and reminding students that kindness is FREE. Jackie stated, ‚ÄúYour future is not set, but you are writing your resume everyday. Make sure you are writing a good one.‚Äù

To support Jordyn‚Äôs cause, WMS teachers purchased and wore the shirts for the assembly.

For more information about the project, or to purchase shirts, visit: www.bekindtoeveryone.com.

post_text: Take a look at the latest tree art at Martin Warren Elementary! The students in fourth grade were learning how to create radial weavings on simple paper plate looms in Mrs. Escobar's art class. Her student teacher, Ms. Worley from UCM, suggested that we install a "yarn bombing" (instillation art in which objects in a public place are covered in a weaving) on a near by tree in the outdoor classroom at Martin Warren. As soon as we told the students about it, they were super excited! It makes you look at the space in a whole new way!

post_text: Throughout February, our school district has celebrated Black History month in numerous ways. For example, at Martin Warren Elementary School, students learned why we celebrate Black History Month and began focusing on influential African American's that impact our lives today. They learned about Rosa Parks, Ruby Bridges, Martin Luther King Jr, Jackie Robinson, Dred Scott and Richard & Mildred Loving. Students compared and contrasted 1st and 2nd hand accounts of events told from multiple perspectives. Another group did a close read of Dr. Martin Luther King‚Äôs Letter from the Birmingham Jail, and students also learned about other Civil Rights activities while watching videos about the Freedom Riders and Lunch Counter Sit-ins.

post_text:
Congratulations to the following students who have received recognition or an award from the 2018 Missouri Writing Region of the Scholastic Writing Awards Contest. Their pieces were selected from over 1,000 submissions from throughout Missouri and the Kansas City, Kansas, area. Their works will be published in Missouri Youth Write, an online publication available in June 2018. In addition, these students will be honored at The Scholastic Writing Awards Ceremony & Reception at the Write to Learn Conference on Friday, February 17, 2018 in Osage Beach, Missouri.

The students who earned awards for their works are as follows:

Tiffany Liu won a Silver Key for her flash fiction, "The Children, the Stars, and the Sky."

Jonathan Larimore won Honorable Mention for his short story, "Anna."

Jessica Paxton won Honorable Mention for her writing portfolio, "Life and all her Pleasurable Woes."

Please, join us in congratulating these students for their phenomenal accomplishments!

post_text: Last week an assembly was held at WHS for all sophomores. Sgt. Stosberg from the Missouri State Highway Patrol talked about the main causes of automobile crashes, how to prevent crashes and how to stay safe while driving. Hillary from ThinkFirst Missouri discussed an accident that left her partially paralyzed from the waist down. She discussed her life before and after her accident and how she could have made better choices to prevent this from happening. Thank you MSHP and ThinkFirst Missouri.

Congratulations to Mr. Woods Prael on his accomplishments this year!

Mr. Prael was selected by The New York Times to be interviewed about a lesson he created in relation to the Charlottesville tragedy. His lesson was selected from hundreds of lessons submitted by teachers nationally. Here is the link: https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/28/learning/lesson-plans/teachers-charlottesville-curriculim.html

Mr. Prael was also selected from hundreds of applicants to present at the Missouri Write to Learn Conference in February. Write to Learn is a conference "designed for All K-12 Language Arts Teachers and sponsored by the Missouri State Council of ILA, the Missouri Reading Initiative, The Missouri Writing Projects Network, and the Missouri Council of Teachers of English." His presentation is called "Horror Literature for the At Risk Population."

We are so proud of Mr. Prael!

The Missouri Council of Teachers of Mathematics (MCTM) held its annual Fall Conference on December 1-2, 2017 in Columbia, MO. On Friday, December 1, our own Dona Rich was recognized as the Outstanding High School Educator of 2017 for the State of Missouri.

Dona is in her tenth year as a teacher at Warrensburg High School. She is a member of multiple professional organizations, has presented at numerous statewide conferences, and contributed to mathematics work at DESE by item writing and content bias reviews.

Warrensburg is fortunate to have such an outstanding educator, congratulations Mrs. Rich!

post_text: The Warrensburg R-VI School District is proud to announce that our district is now a Green Dot school district! What does this mean? The Green Dot program is a bystander training program designed to deter and combat bullying and other types of violence in our schools. For the majority of our schools, this training focuses on identifying and reporting incidents of bullying behavior in school. Think of every incident of bullying behavior as a red dot in our schools. When a student or staff member does something to help with an incident of bullying, this is an example of a Green Dot. The more Green Dots in our schools, the safer our schools become! As the year progresses, we will be highlighting the various programs in each of our schools as they implement Green Dot. Stay tuned!
